-- Adidas, Audi, BMW, Deutsche Post, VW: German Equity Preview
-- B y   H o l g e r   E l f e s   a n d   J u l i e   C r u z
-- 2010-11-15T07:55:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-14/adidas-audi-bmw-deutsche-post-vw-may-be-active-german-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in Germany. Stock
symbols are in parentheses and prices are from the previous
close.  DAX Index futures expiring in December lost 0.4 percent to
6,714 as of 8:13 a.m. in Frankfurt. The benchmark  DAX Index  rose
0.2 percent to 6,734.61 on Nov. 12.  Adidas AG  (ADS GY): The sporting-goods maker sees annual
sales of more than 1 billion euros ($1.37 billion) for its new
Neo fashion brand by 2015,  WirtschaftsWoche  reported, citing
board member  Erich Stamminger . Neo products will cost about 10
percent more than items at Hennes & Mauritz AB and be priced
similar to apparel from Inditex SA’s Zara brand. The shares fell
1.2 percent to 48.85 euros.  Audi AG  (NSU GY): Volkswagen AG’s luxury car maker has a
record order backlog for its vehicles because of increased
demand,  Bild am Sonntag  reported, citing spokeswoman  Esther Bahne . Buyers of Audi’s A3 model have to wait five months for
delivery, the newspaper said. The shares were unchanged at 615
euros.  Bayerische Motoren Werke AG  (BMW GY): The German luxury-car
maker will build its new hybrid sports car from 2014 in the
eastern German city of Leipzig,  Automobilwoche  reported, citing
people close to the company. The car will have a diesel engine
and two electric motors, according to Automobilwoche. The shares
rose 1.6 percent to 55.29 euros.  Deutsche Post AG  (DPW GY): Europe’s biggest mail carrier,
may raise postage prices in 2012 at the earliest,  Frankfurter
Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung  reported, citing Chief Executive
Officer  Frank Appel . Next year domestic postage prices will be
unchanged and the cost of sending letters abroad will be cut,
Appel told the newspaper. The shares rose 2.6 percent to 13.91
euros.  E.ON AG  (EOAN GY): Germany’s largest utility is likely to
focus on selling power grids as it divests 15 billion euros ($21
billion) of assets, luring pension funds hunting for the steady,
inflation-protected returns electricity lines offer. The shares
added 0.2 percent to 22.67 euros.  Gesco AG  (GSC GY): The holding company focusing on machine
tools and engineering posted a 34 percent increase in first-half
net income to 5.7 million euros, as sales and order intake
increased. The shares fell 1.2 percent to 45.44 euros.  Q-Cells SE  (QCE GY): The solar company was raised to
“hold” from “sell” at Societe Generale SA. The shares gained
10 percent to 2.95 euros.  Rheinmetall AG  (RHM GY): The engineering group reported
nine-month earnings before interest and taxes of 173 million
euros, as sales increased. The shares rose 0.1 percent to 51.81
euros.  Volkswagen AG  (VOW GY): The German carmaker wants to
increase its stake in Swedish truckmaker Scania AB to between 75
percent and 80 percent,  Spiegel  reported, citing company
documents. VW holds 46 percent of Scania and plans to raise that
stake and to transfer to Scania its almost 30 percent of German
truck producer MAN SE, the news magazine said. Scania may then
offer to buy out other MAN shareholders after the transfer,
Spiegel said. The preferred shares rose 3.1 percent to 114
euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Holger Elfes  in Dusseldorf at 
 helfes@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Celeste Perri at   cperri@bloomberg.net . 